\section{Discussion and Limitations}
\label{sec:discussion}

The present framework contributes a physically interpretable diagnostic bridge between sparse tower observations and high-order spectral representations. Its main technical advantage is not only the use of a compactified coordinate, but the fact that the compactification, the manifold mass matrix, and the SVD-truncated inversion remain mutually consistent. In practice, that consistency allows the method to resolve near-surface inversion structure while avoiding the artificial degrees of freedom that typically appear when underdetermined tower profiles are regularized too aggressively. The resulting rank compression is therefore informative in a physical sense: low-dimensional wave states are not imposed by the numerics, but emerge because the observations occupy a genuinely restricted subspace.

These diagnostics also suggest a more physically grounded interpretation of regime transitions in the stable boundary layer. The identified thresholds in $D_{\mathrm{eff}}$ and $F_W$ should be compared, in future work, with independent stratified-turbulence scaling measures such as the Ozmidov scale and mixing-efficiency-based state indicators \citep{Li2016, Garanaik2019}. Such comparisons would test whether the empirically observed low-rank wave states coincide with the onset of buoyancy control over shear production, and whether the intermittent regime identified here corresponds to a distinct mixing state rather than a purely statistical bridge between clusters.

The results also fit naturally within the broader wave--turbulence interaction literature. In particular, the present decomposition is compatible with the view that nocturnal boundary layers contain vertically and temporally distinct wave-active and turbulence-active sublayers rather than a single homogeneous stable regime \citep{Sun2015, Barbano2022}. What this manuscript adds is a metric-aware modal coordinate system for diagnosing that structure from sparse profiles, while preserving direct links to upper-boundary absorption tests and manifold rank.

Three limitations remain important. First, the analysis is restricted to a single tower column and therefore cannot directly recover horizontal phase propagation or coherence length scales of submeso motions. Second, the stretching parameter $\alpha_{\mathrm{stretch}}$ is still a calibration choice and should be stress-tested across contrasting campaigns such as Arctic and midlatitude stable layers before it is treated as universal. Third, the present work is diagnostic rather than predictive: extending it to a fully transient nonlinear solver will require explicit anti-aliasing, stable time integration, and carefully designed spectral filtering or viscosity operators in coefficient space \citep{Halila2019, Kaur2023, Pellegrino2023}. Controlled laboratory analogues of stratified transition may provide a useful intermediate validation environment for those developments \citep{Lefauve2025}.

Taken together, these points suggest that the most promising next step is not to replace existing similarity theory with a single new closure, but to build regime-aware parameterizations that condition diffusivity and wave drag on manifold state. In that role, the present framework is best viewed as an observationally constrained state estimator for wave--turbulence partitioning in strongly stable flows.

